AGI - The extraordinary summit of the Arab League, attended by the United Nations, the European Union and the African Union, adopted the plan to rebuild the Gaza Strip presented by Egypt. This was announced by Egyptian President Abdel Fattah al-Sisi during the closing session of the summit in the new administrative capital of Egypt, east of Cairo. The plan was developed in <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2025-02-05/critical-plan-trump-gaza-29879143/"> responded to that of US President Donald Trump </a> to expel over two million Palestinians > from the enclave and turn it into the "Mediterranean Riviera". >
<br> Al-Sisi, who chaired the summit, said that the adoption took place after the Foreign Ministers yesterday drafted the final communiqué and expressed his gratitude to the Arab League for organizing this "important" summit in a "short period". He also thanked for their contribution the various Heads of State and Ministers, as well as the Secretary General of the United Nations, Antonio Guterres, and the President of the European Council, Antonio Costa.
<br The plan of reconstruction of the Gaza Strip, > devastated by the war, will take more than five years and 53 billion dollars.>&nbsp; Initially, there will be a phase of "premature recovery" of six months, > during which $3 billion will be spent to carry out the first works of removal of rubble and prepare seven areas of the Strip to temporarily accommodate more than 1.5 million Palestinians. The work will be supervised by a committee composed of Palestinian technocrats.
<br> It will follow a two-year phase to complete the process of remediation of debris and restoration of about 60,000 "partially destroyed" houses, followed by a final phase of the duration of two and a half years that will require another $30 billion.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
During the summit, Al-Sisi called for an international conference to be held in Egypt to mobilize regional and international funds to finance the reconstruction of the Palestinian enclave. &nbsp;
Israel rejects the plan
Israel rejects the declaration of the Arab summit in Cairo to discuss the reconstruction of Gaza. The summit, read in a note of the Foreign Ministry of Tel aviv, failed to address the reality of the situation after the massacre of Hamas of 7 October 2023.<br> "It is worth noting that the ferocious terrorist attack of Hamas is not mentioned and that there is not even a condemnation of this homicidal terrorist entity, despite documented atrocities," reads in the note that praises the plan of the President of the United States Donald Trump to transfer citizens of Gaza.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

